            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-97-person1262">
                  JEREMIAH
                   HARRIS
               <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1262" type="surname" value="HARRIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1262" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1262" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             Sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a <rs id="t17940917-97-viclabel501" type="occupation">linen-draper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-97-victim1261 t17940917-97-viclabel501"></join>; I was robbed on Friday the 12th of February, between the hours of twelve and one; I was not at home.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-97-person1263">
                  WILLIAM
                   TIERS
               <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1263" type="surname" value="TIERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1263" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1263" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a watchmaker by trade, and a constable.</p>
               <p>Q. Was you in the shop at the time? - No; there was nobody at home at the time. Two women came into the shop, and informed Mr. Harris's shopman that he had lost something.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-97-person1264">
                  JOHN
                   WILLIAMS
               <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1264" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1264" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             Sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a pawnbroker's servant; I produce a calico shawl; the prisoner at the bar brought it to me on the 12th of September, between the hours of one and two.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you ever seen her before? - Never.</p>
               <p>Q. In what name was it pawned? - In the name of Ann Hall, her own name.</p>
               <p>Tiers. Between one and two o'clock, nearly about two, on Friday, the 12th of September, the prosecutor came to me, and informed me he had lost a shawl, and he strongly suspected a person whom I knew; and I went to the lodging of the prisoner, and found her on the bed; I awakened her, and told her she was suspected of stealing a shawl.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179409170224"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-97-person1265">
                  Q. 
               <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1265" type="given" value="Q."></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-person1265" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            What time did you go to her? -  Nearly about two. She said she had never been out of the room that day. I took her into custody, and searched her, and found the ticket on her; and that led to the pawnbroker. This is it.</p>
               <p>Pawnbroker. This is my duplicate.</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. This is my shawl. She did not cut it from the other shawls at the door; it was tore off; I left it hanging at the door; I see it there about eleven o'clock in the morning. There is a space left between, to cut them with the scissars; and she tore it, instead of cutting it.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you think she did it at the door? - Yes, I think so.</p>
               <p>Q. Is it easily done? - No, it is not; I have brought one shawl here to compare with it.</p>
               <p>Q. From the circumstance of that being the same pattern, can you swear that to be your's? - I have no doubt about it; not in the least.</p>
               <p>Q. Was there any shopman in the shop at this time? - Yes; there were two shopmen, but they don't know who took it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was going along Golden-lane about three o'clock in the afternoon, a woman comes up to me, and asked me to buy an handkerchief; she said I should have it for two shillings and three-pence. I said, I had no money but nine-pence in my pocket; says she, will you go and pawn it for eighteen-pence, and you shall have the duplicate for the other nine-pence; and I went and pawned it for eighteen pence; and came out and gave her the duplicate. The pawnbroker see me; and I gave her the other nine-pence for the duplicate, not knowing that it was stole, or else I would not have done it.</p>
               <p>Jury to Williams. Did you see the prisoner give a woman eighteen-pence? - I did not.</p>
               <p>Q. Was there any woman with her? - There were two women with her.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17940917-97-verdict502" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17940917-97-verdict502" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               Not GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the London Jury before Mr. RECORDER.</p>
